‚ĚáÔłŹChapter 1 ¬∑ Foundations
ūüíĘWhat is Java?
Java is a programming language ‚ÄĒ a formal way to give instructions to a computer ‚ÄĒ created by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems in 1995. Its motto was "Write Once, Run Anywhere."

ūüíĘThe big idea
Every computer understands only one language: binary (0s and 1s). Java lets you write human-readable instructions that get converted to something every computer can run ‚ÄĒ regardless of whether it's Windows, Mac, or Linux.

ūüíĘWhy Java became huge
> It runs on billions of devices ‚ÄĒ phones, servers, ATMs, smart TVs
> Android apps were originally written in Java
> It powers the backend of Netflix, LinkedIn, Amazon
> It is strongly typed ‚ÄĒ the language catches your mistakes early
> It is object-oriented ‚ÄĒ everything in Java is modelled as real-world "things"
Java is not JavaScript
--> Java and JavaScript are completely different languages. JavaScript runs in browsers. Java runs in the JVM. The name similarity is purely marketing from 1995.
Java versions (quick map)
Era	     Version	        What changed
Classic	 Java 1‚Äď4	        The original language
Modern	 Java 5‚Äď8	        Generics, lambdas, streams
Current	 Java 17‚Äď21(LTS)	Records, sealed classes, pattern matching
The language you learn today is the same core Java that has been used since 1995. The new versions add features, they don't break what you learn here.


‚ĚáÔłŹChapter 2 ¬∑ Foundations
How Java works
Before you write a single line, you need to understand the invisible machine that runs your code. This is the part most courses skip.

ūüíĘThe three pieces
Thing	                          What it is	                                  Analogy
JDK ‚ÄĒ Java Development Kit	    The full toolkit to write + compile Java	    A kitchen with all equipment
JRE ‚ÄĒ Java Runtime Environment	Only what's needed to run Java programs	      The kitchen for eating, not cooking
JVM ‚ÄĒ Java Virtual Machine	    The engine that actually executes your code	  The chef who reads and executes the recipe
The journey of your code
When you write Java, here is exactly what happens:

Step 1: You write human-readable code
  MyProgram.java

Step 2: The compiler (javac) translates it to bytecode
  javac MyProgram.java  ‚Üí  MyProgram.class

Step 3: The JVM reads the .class file and runs it on YOUR machine
  java MyProgram  ‚Üí  output appears
ūüíĘWhat is bytecode?
It's not binary, it's not Java. It's an in-between language that the JVM understands. This is why Java runs on every OS ‚ÄĒ the bytecode is the same, but each OS has its own JVM that translates it.

Install the JDK 21 (from oracle.com or adoptium.net). It includes the compiler AND the JVM. You only ever need to install this one thing.
Compiled vs Interpreted
Java is both. It is compiled (your code ‚Üí bytecode) and then interpreted/JIT-compiled by the JVM at runtime. This gives you the safety of compilation and the flexibility of interpretation.


