‚ĚáÔłŹChapter 12 ¬∑ OOP
ūüíĘEncapsulation
Encapsulation means hiding the internal details and only exposing what is necessary. It's the "what you need to know" principle.

ūüíĘThe problem without encapsulation
// Without encapsulation ‚ÄĒ anyone can set any value
Dog d = new Dog();
d.age = -500;  // This is wrong! A dog can't be -500 years old.
The solution: private fields + public getters/setters
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance;  // private = only accessible inside this class

    public BankAccount(double initialBalance) {
        if (initialBalance >= 0) {
            this.balance = initialBalance;
        }
    }

    // Getter ‚ÄĒ read the value
    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    // Setter ‚ÄĒ set the value with validation
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid deposit amount");
        }
    }
}
ūüíĘAccess modifiers
Modifier	        Who can access it
private	Only      within the same class
default (none)	  Within the same package
protected	Same    package + subclasses
public	          Everyone, everywhere
Rule of thumb: make all fields private. Expose them via public getters/setters. This protects your data.


‚ĚáÔłŹChapter 13 ¬∑ OOP
ūüíĘInheritance
Inheritance lets one class inherit the fields and methods of another. It models "is-a" relationships ‚ÄĒ a Dog IS-A Animal.

Parent class (superclass)
public class Animal {
    String name;

    public Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void breathe() {
        System.out.println(name + " is breathing");
    }

    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("...");
    }
}
Child class (subclass)
public class Dog extends Animal {  // "extends" = inherit from
    String breed;

    public Dog(String name, String breed) {
        super(name);  // calls Animal's constructor
        this.breed = breed;
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {  // overrides Animal's makeSound
        System.out.println(name + " says: Woof!");
    }

    public void fetch() {  // Dog-only method
        System.out.println(name + " fetches the ball!");
    }
}

Dog d = new Dog("Bruno", "Lab");
d.breathe();    // inherited from Animal
d.makeSound();  // Dog's overridden version
d.fetch();      // Dog's own method
Key keywords
extends ‚ÄĒ creates the inheritance relationship
super() ‚ÄĒ calls the parent class constructor
super.method() ‚ÄĒ calls the parent class method
@Override ‚ÄĒ annotation that says "I'm replacing a parent method"
Java does NOT support multiple inheritance (a class can't extend two classes). But it can implement multiple interfaces (chapter 15).


‚ĚáÔłŹChapter 14 ¬∑ OOP
ūüíĘPolymorphism
Polymorphism means "many forms." The same method name behaves differently depending on the object. One interface, many behaviours.

ūüíĘRuntime polymorphism
