Animal a = new Dog("Rex", "GSD");

if (a instanceof Dog) {
    Dog d = (Dog) a;  // downcast to Dog
    d.fetch();         // now you can use Dog-only methods
}

// Pattern matching (Java 16+) ‚ÄĒ cleaner:
if (a instanceof Dog d) {
    d.fetch();  // no need to cast manually
}


‚ĚáÔłŹChapter 15 ¬∑ OOP
ūüíĘAbstraction & interfaces
Abstraction means defining WHAT something does, without specifying HOW. Two tools: abstract classes and interfaces.

ūüíĘAbstract class
abstract class Shape {
    abstract double area();   // no body ‚ÄĒ subclass MUST implement
    abstract double perimeter();

    public void describe() {  // can have normal methods too
        System.out.println("Area: " + area());
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    double r;
    Circle(double r) { this.r = r; }

    @Override double area() { return Math.PI * r * r; }
    @Override double perimeter() { return 2 * Math.PI * r; }
}
ūüíĘInterface ‚ÄĒ a contract
interface Flyable {
    void fly();            // all methods are abstract by default
    default void land() {  // default methods have a body
        System.out.println("Landing...");
    }
}

interface Swimmable {
    void swim();
}

// A class CAN implement multiple interfaces
class Duck extends Animal implements Flyable, Swimmable {
    public Duck(String name) { super(name); }

    @Override public void fly() { System.out.println("Duck flying"); }
    @Override public void swim() { System.out.println("Duck swimming"); }
    @Override public void makeSound() { System.out.println("Quack!"); }
}
                      Abstract class	            Interface
Has constructors	    Yes	                        No
Has fields	          Yes	                        Only static final
Multiple inheritance	No (extends 1)	            Yes (implements many)
Purpose	              Shared base behavior	      Define a contract/capability


